# Security Guidelines

Directives for secure coding. Apply when handling input, identity, secrets, or sensitive data.

---

## Input Validation

- Validate all caller-supplied data at the boundary — type, format, range, and length
- Reject invalid input explicitly; do not sanitise and proceed
- Use schema validation (e.g. Zod, FluentValidation) for structured input
- Enforce length limits to prevent buffer overflow and DoS
- Validate file uploads: type allowlist, size limits, and content inspection
- Validate URLs before use: allowlist scheme and host; reject `file://`, `localhost`, internal IPs

**Parameterised queries only:**
```sql
-- Good: parameterised
SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1
-- Bad: string concatenation
SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = '${id}'
```

---

## Authentication

- Verify identity before checking permissions; never allow partial or anonymous access to sensitive operations
- Hash passwords with bcrypt (salt rounds ≥ 12) or Argon2; never store plaintext
- JWT: use short expiry (≤ 15 min for access tokens); validate issuer, audience, and expiry; use strong secret
- Prefer refresh tokens for session extension; store securely (httpOnly, secure, SameSite)
- Enable MFA for privileged or sensitive operations
- Implement rate limiting on login and password-reset endpoints
- Use constant-time comparison for tokens and secrets

---

## Authorisation

- Authorise at the resource level; verify the authenticated user may access the specific resource requested
- Do not rely only on role checks; verify resource ownership in business logic
- Default to deny; require explicit grant for elevated access
- Missing authorisation on one endpoint is an access control failure
- Implement RBAC with least privilege; map roles to permissions explicitly

---

## Data Protection

- Encrypt sensitive data at rest (AES-256-GCM) and in transit (TLS 1.2+)
- Use platform-provided crypto; never implement custom algorithms
- Never use MD5 or SHA-1 for security purposes; use SHA-256 or higher
- Store keys in a secrets manager; inject at runtime; rotate on compromise
- Enforce HSTS for web applications
- Use secure defaults: restrict CORS, disable debug in production

---

## XSS Prevention

- Escape output in rendering contexts; do not trust stored data as safe
- Use framework escaping (e.g. React’s default) or a sanitiser (e.g. DOMPurify) for HTML
- Forbid `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` / `innerHTML` with user content unless sanitised
- Set `Content-Security-Policy` to restrict script sources
- Disallow `javascript:` URLs and event handlers in user input

---

## CSRF Prevention

- Use CSRF tokens for state-changing operations (POST, PUT, DELETE)
- Validate token on server; use constant-time comparison
- Set `SameSite=Strict` or `Lax` on cookies
- Prefer SameSite cookies over custom tokens where sufficient

---

## SSRF Prevention

- Allowlist outbound URLs; validate scheme (https only) and host
- Block `localhost`, internal IPs, and cloud metadata endpoints
- Do not fetch user-supplied URLs without validation
- Use a proxy or allowlist for external requests

---

## Security Headers

Set these HTTP headers:

| Header | Value |
|--------|-------|
| `X-Content-Type-Options` | `nosniff` |
| `X-Frame-Options` | `DENY` or `SAMEORIGIN` |
| `X-XSS-Protection` | `1; mode=block` |
| `Strict-Transport-Security` | `max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains` |
| `Content-Security-Policy` | Restrict script, style, and connect sources |
| `Referrer-Policy` | `strict-origin-when-cross-origin` |

---

## Error Responses

- Return generic messages to unauthenticated or unauthorised callers
- Do not expose stack traces, database errors, or internal paths in API responses
- Log detailed errors server-side; return minimal details client-side
- Use consistent error format (e.g. `{ "error": "code", "message": "..." }`)

---

## Logging

- Never log: passwords, tokens, API keys, full PAN/CVV, national IDs, or PII combinations
- Log security events: auth failures, access denied, privilege changes
- Use structured logging; mask or exclude sensitive fields at the log sink
- Alert on auth anomalies and repeated failures

---

## Dependency Hygiene

- Run `npm audit` / `pip audit` / equivalent in CI; fail on high/critical
- Update dependencies regularly; remove unused packages
- Prefer signed packages and verified sources
- Pin versions; review changelogs before upgrades

---

## OWASP Top 10 Quick Reference

| Risk | Mitigation |
|------|------------|
| A01 Broken access control | Authorise at boundary and resource level |
| A02 Cryptographic failures | Use standard libraries; enforce TLS; no MD5/SHA-1 |
| A03 Injection | Parameterise all queries; validate all inputs |
| A04 Insecure design | Threat model; architecture review |
| A05 Security misconfiguration | Remove defaults; restrict CORS; disable debug in prod |
| A06 Vulnerable components | Automated scanning; regular updates |
| A07 Auth and session failures | Short token TTL; validate JWT claims; MFA for sensitive ops |
| A08 Software and data integrity | Signed packages; secure CI/CD |
| A09 Logging and monitoring failures | Structured logs; alert on auth anomalies |
| A10 SSRF | Allowlist outbound URLs; validate scheme and host |

---

## Security Checklist

- [ ] All inputs validated at the boundary
- [ ] Parameterised queries or ORM for all DB access
- [ ] No secrets in code or committed config
- [ ] Endpoints require auth unless explicitly public
- [ ] Resource ownership verified in handlers
- [ ] No sensitive data in logs
- [ ] Dependencies current; no high/critical CVEs
- [ ] Error responses do not reveal internals
- [ ] TLS enforced; HSTS configured for web apps
- [ ] Security headers set
- [ ] CSRF protection for state-changing operations
- [ ] Rate limiting on auth endpoints
